Flight tracking systems used by transportation companies typically monitor major delays but miss shorter delays or gate changes that affect passenger timing. Drivers usually receive updates about delays over 45 minutes, but delays of 20-30 minutes often don't trigger automatic notifications. This means passengers may arrive to find their driver isn't aware of timing changes.

Communication procedures during delays vary significantly between companies. Some maintain direct phone contact between passengers and drivers, while others route all communication through dispatch centers. Direct contact usually works better for real-time coordination, but dispatch-based systems may provide more professional backup support when problems arise.

Driver scheduling policies affect service quality during delay situations. Companies that schedule drivers for single trips can often wait indefinitely for delayed flights without affecting other customers. However, companies that schedule drivers for multiple trips per day may need to reassign drivers when delays exceed certain thresholds, potentially affecting service consistency.

